    <property>
      <category>Misleading Wording</category>
    </property>
    <property>
      <description>Using the wrong tense on purpose.  For example, saying "Medicare For All is a mess" is misleading because it doesn't exist yet. It should be "...will be.." or "...may be..." rather than "...is...". By using "is", the author attempts to make it seem as if there is only one "Medicare For All" proposal, when there are many varied proposals. This way, the author can then criticise this one proposal without saying which proposal he's actually criticising, and avoid dealing with the fact that perhaps the criticism doesn't apply to many of the proposals.</description>
